#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1891
# be148c1999354445b3ef036cda8e7318
msgid "Map production is the process of arranging map elements on a sheet of paper in a way that, even without many words, the average person can understand what it is all about. Maps are usually produced for presentations and reports where the audience or reader is a politician, citizen or a learner with no professional background in GIS. Because of this, a map has to be effective in communicating spatial information. Common elements of a map are the title, map body, legend, north arrow, scale bar, acknowledgement, and map border (see  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1900
# 5f9ee7374ae04196b952526aa977331d
msgid "Other elements that might be added are e.g. a **graticule**, or **name of the ****map projection** (CRS). Together, these elements help the map reader to interpret the information shown on the map. The map body is, of course, the most important part of the map because it contains the map information. The other elements support the communication process and help the map reader to orientate himself and understand the map topic. For example, the title describes the subject matter and the legend relates map symbols to the mapped data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1907
# 4ffd606d33d148a684bf51a6015396cc
msgid "Title in detail:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1909
# 5c92ed6571214321ba5551d4343f2978
msgid "The map title is very important because it is usually the first thing a reader will look at on a map. It can be compared with a title in a newspaper. It should be short but give the reader a first idea of what the map is about."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1913
# da1cece7ffe34146ba99750d5f340486
msgid "Map Border in detail:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1915
# 36fb6d81e2c14ca29c61ad84f021f975
msgid "The map border is a line that defines exactly the edges of the area shown on the map. When printing a map with a graticule (which we describe further down), you often find the coordinate information of the graticule lines along the border lines, as you can see in  ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1918
# f62c3c9114364f718dc31b4c9e1871e3
msgid "Map Legend in detail:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1920
# fb4e5c9010cc4d32a301a852484e2c08
msgid "A map is a simplified representation of the real world and **map symbols** are used to represent real objects. Without symbols, we wouldn't understand maps. To ensure that a person can correctly read a map, a map legend is used to provide a key to all the symbols used on the map. It is like a dictionary that allows you to understand the meaning of what the map shows. A map legend is usually shown as a little box in a corner of the map. It contains icons, each of which will represent a type of feature. For example, a *house* icon will show you how to identify houses on the map (see  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1933
# 9cee188c7ecc42edb64f117e22d073c4
msgid "You can also use different symbols and icons in your legend to show different themes. In   you can see a map with a lake in light blue overlaid with contour lines and spot heights to show information about the terrain in that area. On the right side you see the same area with the lake in the background but this map is designed to show tourists the location of houses they can rent for their holidays. It uses brighter colours, a house icon and more descriptive and inviting words in the legend."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1939
# 5501ab474af949cf83ec2bf9d2866e95
msgid "North arrow in detail:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1941
# 5795a508e0ce4787b385feea7699be88
msgid "A north arrow (sometimes also called a compass rose) is a figure displaying the main directions, **North, South, East** and **West**. On a map it is used to indicate the direction of North."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1945
# 8c3b2c7a4ca64214a666399b900385a5
msgid "For example, in GIS this means that a house that is located north from a lake can be found on top of the lake on a map. The road in the east will then be to the right of the water body on the map, a river in the south will be below the water body and if you are searching for a train station to the west of the lake you will find it on the left side on the map."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1949
# 30a1a2da13184630ae6c40dc0b6a9c55
msgid "Scale in detail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1951
# 4a30d37868a64000976befcf76bd35b2
msgid "The scale of a map, is the value of a single unit of distance on the map, representing distance in the real world. The values are shown in map units (meters, feet or degrees). The scale can be expressed in several ways, for example, in words, as a ratio or as a graphical scale bar (see  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1955
# b80e592a86a44742be13194464f81e78
msgid "**Expressing a scale in words** is a commonly used method and has the advantage of being easily understood by most map users. You can see an example of a word based scale in a . Another option is the **representative fraction (RF)** method, where both the map distance and the ground distance in the real world are given in the same map units, as a ratio. For example, a RF value 1:25,000 means that any distance on the map is 1/25,000*th* of the real distance on the ground (see b ). The value 25,000 in the ratio is called the **scale denominator**. More experienced users often prefer the representative fraction method, because it reduces confusion."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1962
# 22986e55fe32404a82fb44edcf767945
msgid "When a representative fraction expresses a very small ratio, for example 1:1000 000, it is called a **small scale map**.** **On the other hand if the ratio is very large, for example a 1:50 000 map, it is called a **large scale map**. It is handy to remember that a small scale map covers a **large area**, and a large scale map covers a **small area**!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1965
# 6a59d8c6bf2343bc8b6c1abf20b696e6
msgid "A **scale expression as a graphic or bar scale** is another basic method of expressing a scale. A bar scale shows measured distances on the map. The equivalent distance in the real world is placed above as you can see in c ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1973
# 089f213a38f04b3bb867b66941c1fe3c
msgid "Maps are usually produced at standard scales of, for example, 1:10 000, 1:25 000, 1:50 000, 1:100 000, 1:250 000, 1:500 000. What does this mean to the map reader? It means that if you *multiply* the distance measured on the **map** by the **scale denominator**, you will know the distance in the **real world**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1975
# 1e0dcf0b3d304702a130dda86433ecaa
msgid "For example, if we want to measure a distance of 100mm on a map with a scale of 1:25,000 we calculate the real world distance like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1977
# 49e55d7269bd497fb98e6ad3fcdeb300
msgid "100mm x 25,000 = 2,500,000 mm"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1979
# 13af910969a249d78c67ef64af5e5f19
msgid "This means that 100mm on the map is equivalent to 2,500,000mm (250m) in the real word."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1982
# fffa94ee797b40739df1cf5f26870012
msgid "Another interesting aspect of a map scale, is that the lower the map scale, the more detailed the feature information in the map will be. In  , you can see an example of this. Both maps are the same size but have a different scale. The image on the left side shows more details, for example the houses south-west of the water body can be clearly identified as separate squares. In the image on the right you can only see a black clump of rectangles and you are not able to see each house clearly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1992
# 9df0fe986d594b9796cb31797672c5bd
msgid "Acknowledgment in detail:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:1994
# 64946f0a96814aef96c257da117dd1ee
msgid "In the acknowledgment area of a map it is possible to add text with important information. For example information about the quality of the used data can be useful to give the reader an idea about details such as how, by whom and when a map was created. If you look at a topographical map of your town, it would be useful to know when the map was created and who did it. If the map is already 50 years old, you will probably find a lot of houses and roads that no longer exist or maybe never even existed. If you know that the map was created by an official institution, you could contact them and ask if they have a more current version of that map with updated information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:2001
# 13a370396882434dbac05e381058cae5
msgid "Graticule in detail:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:2003
# de7ca81362b341b6b26729dcc7edd6e9
msgid "A graticule is a network of lines overlain on a map to make spatial orientation easier for the reader. The lines can be used as a reference. As an example, the lines of a graticule can represent the earth's parallels of latitude and meridians of longitude. When you want to refer to a special area on a map during your presentation or in a report you could say: “the houses close to latitude 26.04 / longitude  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:2012
# cab38d06eea24ca4b078a4395ada0cb2
msgid "Name of the map projection in detail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:2014
# 0c56aea1c6974743bba8ca9c01d5d9a3
msgid "A map projection tries to represent the 3-dimensional Earth with all its features like houses, roads or lakes on a flat sheet of paper. This is very difficult as you can imagine, and even after hundreds of years there is no single projection that is able to represent the Earth perfectly for any area in the world. Every projection has advantages and disadvantages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:2019
# 10826250f70e49179a6def22f8380d19
msgid "To be able to create maps as precisely as possible, people have studied, modified, and produced many different kinds of projections. In the end almost every country has developed its own map projection with the goal of improving the map accuracy for their territorial area (see  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:2027
# 948fcb5cf41f40728c8686f7863a07fe
msgid "With this in mind, we can now understand why it makes sense to add the name of the projection on a map. It allows the reader to see quickly, if one map can be compared with another. For example, features on a map in a so-called *None* projection appear very different to features projected in a *Cylindrical Equidistant* projection (see  )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/gentle_gis_introduction/AGentleIntroductionToGIS.rst:2032
# dc183e60daad44a788c3f8f437b67e18
msgid "Map projection is a very complex topic and we cannot cover it completely here. You may want to take a look at our previous topic: Coordinate Reference Systems if you want to know more about it."
msgstr ""

